          "tool_use_id": "toolu_012XbA7Knq6LaQNp2k5magjL",
          "type": "tool_result",
          "content": "1\t---\n2\ttitle: Coding Stack Preferences\n3\tlast_updated: 2026-04-15\n4\tdomain: coding\n5\tcategory: stack\n6\ttags: [python, defaults, libraries, testing, style]\n7\tdecay: evergreen\n8\t---\n9\t\n10\t# Coding Stack Preferences\n11\t\n12\tJordan's defaults for personal scripts and OSS contributions. The day-job stack at work is separate \u2014 these defaults don't apply to company-project questions unless Jordan asks.\n13\t\n14\t## Language\n15\t\n16\t**Python** \u2014 the default for everything outside work: small scripts, OSS contributions, prototype scratch code. Python 3.11+ is fine; happy to use modern features (`match`, structural typing, walrus when it improves a parser-style loop).\n17\t\n18\tNo Go or TypeScript in personal projects. If something needs to be a single binary, Jordan reaches for a shell script or a small Python with `uv`/`pipx`.\n19\t\n20\t## Library defaults\n21\t\n22\t**Stdlib first.** For OSS contributions especially, Jordan prefers code that reads top-to-bottom with no external dependency \u2014 `heapq`, `collections`, `dataclasses`, `pathlib`, `argparse`. Pulling in a third-party library has to clear a real bar (would be visibly worse without it).\n23\t\n24\tWhen a library is warranted:\n25\t- **CLI:** `argparse` for personal scripts; `click` only when nested subcommand structure makes argparse painful.\n26\t- **HTTP:** `httpx` over `requests` (modern API, sync + async, better timeout defaults).\n27\t- **JSON with validation:** `pydantic` v2 \u2014 only when there's actually untrusted input being parsed, not for every internal data class.\n28\t\n29\t## Testing\n30\t\n31\t- **`pytest` with fixtures** is the standard. `unittest`'s class-based style is allowed in projects that already use it, but Jordan won't introduce it to a new project.\n32\t- New functionality requires a test. Refactors preserve existing tests, not rewrite them.\n33\t- Don't skip or `pytest.mark.skip` without an explicit reason captured in the test body.\n34\t\n35\t## Style\n36\t\n37\t- Type hints on public function signatures and anything non-obvious. Don't bother annotating local variables the type checker can infer.\n38\t- Docstrings for module-level functions and classes; one-liner for short helpers. No \"why\" inside docstrings \u2014 that goes in code comments at the line where the *why* matters.\n39\t- Module structure matches the surrounding project. For small libraries (like `py-graph-algorithms`): one algorithm per file, flat layout, no submodules.\n40\t\n41\t## Things Jordan avoids\n42\t\n43\t- Heavy frameworks for small jobs (Django for a 100-line script; FastAPI for a one-shot CLI).\n44\t- Adding a dependency to an OSS project Jordan didn't start, when the same job can be done with stdlib.\n45\t- Async by default \u2014 only when the workload is actually I/O-bound at scale.\n46\t"
        }
